WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.200
I'm going to switch gears a little bit and talk less about lymphoma and more about a tool that

00:00:05.200 --> 00:00:10.380
can be used to make single-cell DNA sequencing more feasible, much faster, and importantly,

00:00:10.500 --> 00:00:18.220
much less expensive. So what is single-cell DNA sequencing? And may someone want to do it in the

00:00:18.220 --> 00:00:22.680
first place? As we all know, cancer, and particularly leukemias and lymphomas, are

00:00:22.680 --> 00:00:28.340
incredibly heterogeneous. Within a single patient, you can have multiple mutationally driven clones

00:00:28.340 --> 00:00:33.240
and subclones, and these change and evolve with therapeutic pressure. Single-cell sequencing

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:38.740
allows you to resolve this clonal heterogeneity on a single-cell level and restore clonal

00:00:38.740 --> 00:00:44.240
architecture. So for example, the figure here on the left, this is a fish plot. You've probably

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:49.260
seen these before. Fun fact, they're called fish plots because the person that originally made this

00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:55.560
R package thought it looked like a tropical fish. I love that so much. The y-axis is variant allyl

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:58.200
frequency, and the x-axis is time, and each colorful.

00:00:58.340 --> 00:01:03.280
Fish, or section, represents a genetically distinct clone or subclone. And for this

00:01:03.280 --> 00:01:07.800
particular example patient, you can see some clones, like that red clone and that green clone,

00:01:07.880 --> 00:01:13.140
get much smaller on therapy, whereas others, like the blue and the purple, later come back. And

00:01:13.140 --> 00:01:17.300
these have different mutational and commutational patterns, and this is important for understanding

00:01:17.300 --> 00:01:22.500
what is driving drug resistance. Single-cell DNA sequencing is also important for understanding

00:01:22.500 --> 00:01:28.320
tumor phylogeny, or the order in which mutations are acquired. And this is key both for leukemiogenesis,

00:01:28.340 --> 00:01:33.640
but also in drug resistance. And Ross Levine's group has used this technology to do some really

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:38.920
beautiful work, as shown in that middle panel. Finally, in recent years, we now have multi-omics,

00:01:39.420 --> 00:01:44.500
where single-cell DNA sequencing can be combined directly with either single-cell immunophenotyping

00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:49.500
or single-cell RNA sequencing. So now on the single-cell level, we can know the precise

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:55.860
relationship between a cell's genotype and that same cell's immunophenotype. So I could keep going

00:01:55.860 --> 00:01:58.180
on and on with examples like this all day long, but so far, I've been able to do a lot of work on this.

00:01:58.180 --> 00:01:58.320
So I'm going to go ahead and show you a little bit of this. So I'm going to go ahead and show you a little bit of this.

00:01:58.340 --> 00:02:04.540
This is a really fantastic technology. Unfortunately, it's also a very expensive

00:02:04.540 --> 00:02:09.180
technology. And off the shelf, you're usually looking at, nowadays, I think it's around $5,000

00:02:09.180 --> 00:02:14.340
per sample. And this really came clear to me a couple of years ago when I was asked to do

00:02:14.340 --> 00:02:18.920
correlatives for a pediatric trial through COG. And this was a fairly small trial. It was only

00:02:18.920 --> 00:02:24.880
32 patients with three serial samples per patient. But very quickly, I was looking at at least $300,000

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:28.180
for just reagents. And by the time we added in sequencing costs and here's the result,

00:02:28.180 --> 00:02:32.400
and human labor, it was well over half a million dollars. And that was not the only correlative for

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:37.140
this trial. It was actually putting together that budget that made me realize there has got to be a

00:02:37.140 --> 00:02:44.200
better way to think about how we look at this data. So that better way is multiplexing. So on

00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:49.800
a very, very high level, what is multiplexing? Multiplexing is when you take individual samples

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:58.020
from different patients, you combine them into one single tube, you run whatever your assay of

00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:02.640
doing, and then you use bioinformatics to say, "Okay, this cell belongs to this patient,

00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:09.820
this cell belongs to that patient, et cetera, et cetera." There are two broad strokes ways

00:03:09.820 --> 00:03:14.160
in which people may try to do this. The most common by far are barcode-based approaches.

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:19.360
This is somewhat akin to flow cytometry, where before you combine the different samples,

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:23.820
you give each one a cell surface tag, and this can either be truly fluorescent or it

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:27.860
can be an antibody tag, and then you combine all the samples together.

00:03:27.860 --> 00:03:32.500
This is not great. Minding is sort of notoriously promiscuous and moves around a lot, and I found

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:37.180
this to be not a very high-fidelity system. What actually works a lot better are SNP-based

00:03:37.180 --> 00:03:41.080
approaches. We all have very different germline SNPs because we're all different individual

00:03:41.080 --> 00:03:46.140
people, and you can use these differences in single nucleotide polymorphisms to your advantage

00:03:46.140 --> 00:03:50.780
as a sort of endogenous barcode to decide which cell belongs to which individual.

00:03:50.780 --> 00:03:55.320
To connect samples back to their parent, however, you do need to know that individual's germline

00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:57.700
SNP profile, which is not always information we have on hand.

00:03:57.700 --> 00:04:04.400
I like combining things, so I used both in our novel algorithm, which we called SNaCS,

00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:10.780
for single nucleotide and antibody-based cell sorting. On a broad level, SNaCS first uses

00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:17.100
these antibodies, which we called hash antibodies, to divide cells up into two different populations,

00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:21.700
uses these populations to decide which SNPs are most important for classifying samples

00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:27.540
and clusters them, removes multiplets, and then goes back and uses the hash antibodies

00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:29.780
to find cells back to their parent sample.

00:04:29.780 --> 00:04:35.080
SNaCS is an algorithm, an associated R package, I think it runs pretty smoothly, and also

00:04:35.080 --> 00:04:39.560
has a nice data visualization that lets you sort of immediately see how well your multiplexing

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:43.260
worked, and that's shown here on this heat map. I mean, even if you know absolutely nothing

00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:46.920
about how the algorithm works, you can kind of look at this heat map and say, "Hey, I

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:50.460
think there's two different patients here." And in fact, this was two samples multiplexed

00:04:50.460 --> 00:04:51.460
together.

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:56.380
Again, these bars at the top represent the cell surface antibody-based tags, and you

00:04:56.380 --> 00:04:57.380
can see these

00:04:57.380 --> 00:05:02.080
somewhat separate cells out into two different populations. But what really helps are actually

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:06.700
the SNPs. In this case, we found six different germline SNPs that defined our cells into

00:05:06.700 --> 00:05:10.660
two different populations. And this was done with an off-the-shelf AML panel. In fact,

00:05:10.660 --> 00:05:15.160
we didn't enrich for any specific regions, although later we have started adding in SNPs

00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:19.320
that are actually used by the FBI to help with identifying parent samples, and those

00:05:19.320 --> 00:05:22.080
work really well.

00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:27.220
So how well did this work? To figure this out, I used single cell DNA

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:31.580
sequencing experiments on several different AML samples run as singletons, so that's sort

00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:35.180
of the status quo, and then used the same samples and combined them with two samples

00:05:35.180 --> 00:05:38.920
together, three samples together, four, et cetera, et cetera, all the way up to eight

00:05:38.920 --> 00:05:43.700
samples together. I then benchmarked this against other established methods, mainly

00:05:43.700 --> 00:05:50.200
borrowed from the single-cell RNA-seq literature. How did it work? I think pretty well. So this

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:57.060
is the heat map here on the left of accuracy. The more yellow a square is, the more accurate.

00:05:57.060 --> 00:06:02.520
left column and all the other kind of comparison methods are the other columns. That top row is

00:06:02.520 --> 00:06:07.500
two samples multiplexed together, the middle row is three, and the bottom row is four. And as you

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:13.460
can see, accuracy ranged from about 95 to 99% for snacks, which I thought was pretty acceptable.

00:06:15.360 --> 00:06:20.180
A question I had was just how far can you go? So in my experiments, just based on the number

00:06:20.180 --> 00:06:24.320
of samples I had access to, I went up to eight samples multiplexed together, but could you go

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:30.400
even further? To figure this out, I did several simulations using synthetic data and found that

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:37.120
you can really push up to 10 or even 20 samples before your accuracy stops to drop below 90%.

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:42.280
So this works quite well. What seems to matter far more, the actual number of cells you can load

00:06:42.280 --> 00:06:47.520
onto a platform. So for example, I use the Mission BioDNA-Seq platform, which generally lets you get

00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:51.940
about 10,000 cells maximum. So you can imagine if you're multiplexing two samples together,

00:06:51.940 --> 00:06:54.180
10,000 divided by two, that's 5,000 cells.

00:06:54.320 --> 00:07:00.000
10,000 divided by 10 would be 1,000 cells per sample. There probably reaches a limit where you

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.040
say this is not enough cells to make this worth it. For me, I found four samples multiplexed

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:11.120
together worked really well. I consistently got accuracy greater than 95%, had 2,000 to 3,000

00:07:11.120 --> 00:07:15.200
cells per sample, and importantly, cut a correlative budget at almost two-thirds.

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:22.960
So in conclusion, SNATS is an open-source R package, runs in seconds, and enables scalable,

00:07:22.960 --> 00:07:24.120
accurate single-celled DNA analysis. If you have any questions, feel free to reach out to me at

